We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the City Treasurer to develop strategies that would intensify the collections of RPT which includes (a) conduct of frequent tax campaigns; 

(b) coordination with the City Assessor to determine the home/business address of delinquent taxpayers; 

(c) preparation of Notice of Delinquency; and

(d) submission of Certificates of RPT/SET Delinquency on all delinquent RPT/SET accounts to the Sanggunian in compliance to Section 269 of RA 7160 to request for assistance in the enforcement of remedial measures provided in Sections 256 to 258 of RA 7160.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (a) observe fully the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances;
(b) require the City Accountant to issue demand letter to accountable officers to liquidate or return overdue cash advances;




(c) file appropriate legal action, if warranted, to those who still failed to liquidate long outstanding cash advances despite the receipt of demand letter and exhausting all appropriate means to liquidate the same; and 
(d) file the request for authority to write off unliquidated cash advances to the COA Audit Team Leader and/or Supervising Auditor in case of death of accountable officer and other allowable instances as provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 if all the conditions and requirements provided therein could be complied.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the Accountant to (a) observe rules and regulations governing the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances; 
(b) require settlement of cash advances as soon as the purpose of the grant has been served; 


(c) require the submission of lacking documents for the liquidation of cash advances amounting to ₱202,220.00; and 

(d) discontinue  granting of cash advances to elected officials other than for traveling expense.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (a) instruct the City Engineer and the City Planning Development Officer to monitor and supervise the implementation of the different development projects of the City to ensure their completion on time; 
(b) immediately look into the unimplemented projects and identify causes of non-implementation and develop specific solution to effectively implement the projects; and
 (c) require the budget officer to provide specific projects to be funded from the 20% Development Fund for SP’s approval instead of lump sum appropriations, otherwise, SP approval or resolution is required before entering into contract.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (a) prepare guidelines on conducting a team building to achieve their objectives in the most efficient, economical and orderly manner; 


(b) refrain from conducting out-of-town meeting and team building outside the region; and 


(c) submit the required accomplishment report for the activities undertaken.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that Local Chief Executive 

(a) observe fully the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances; 

(b) require the accountable officers to liquidate overdue cash advances; 

(c) file appropriate legal action, if warranted, to those who failed to liquidate long outstanding cash advances after exhausting appropriate means including those who are no longer in service; and 

(d) file the request for authority to write off unliquidated cash advances to the COA Audit Team Leader and/or Supervising Auditor pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 if all the conditions and requirements provided therein could be complied.

We recommended that the management 

(a) adhere to the guidelines set under items 5.1 and 5.2 of NDRRMC-DBM-DILG JMC No. 2013-001 in utilization of the DRRM Fund to ensure its optimal utilization; 

(b) comply with the provisions contained under Section 5.1.5 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 dated September 12, 2012 regarding submission of the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF; 

(c) employ/appoint personnel to fill up the mandatory positions in accordance with the qualification standards prescribed in NDRRMC, DILG, DBM and CSC JMC No. 2014-1; and 

(d) require the acting LDRRM Officer or City Engineer to monitor the projects and programs of DRRM to ensure its implementation and completion on time.
